You are part of an SRE team managing a microservices application deployed on Kubernetes. One of the critical services (payment-service) is running inside a container.

Recently, alerts started firing because the service is intermittently going down. On investigation, you notice:

Pods are restarting frequently
kubectl describe pod shows: Last State: Terminated (Exit Code: 137)
Application logs do not show any clear error before termination
CPU usage looks normal, but memory usage spikes occasionally

What does exit code 137 indicate in this scenario?
Why might this issue not appear directly in application logs?
How would you confirm the root cause of the problem?
What are the possible reasons for this happening in a Kubernetes environment?

Here are concise interview-ready answers (1–2 lines each):

❓ What does Exit Code 137 indicate?

Exit code 137 means the container was forcefully killed (SIGKILL), most commonly due to Out Of Memory (OOMKilled) by the Kubernetes/node kernel.

❓ Why might this not appear in application logs?

Because the process is terminated abruptly by the system, not by the application itself, so it doesn’t get time to log final errors or shutdown gracefully.

❓ How would you confirm root cause?

I would check kubectl describe pod for OOMKilled reason, node memory metrics, and dmesg/CloudWatch logs to confirm kernel memory kill events.

❓ Possible reasons in Kubernetes?

Common causes include memory limit too low, memory leak in application, sudden traffic spike, inefficient GC, or multiple pods competing for node memory.

