Design a Docker-based deployment pipeline for a growing startup's web application

Case Background
A small startup needs to modernize its deployment workflow. Your decisions will shape how the team ships code moving forward.

Scenario Brief
BrightCart is a 12-person e-commerce startup running a Node.js (Express) web application that serves a product catalog and checkout API. The app currently runs on a single Ubuntu VM managed by one developer who SSHs in, pulls from main, runs 'npm install', and restarts the process using pm2. Deployments happen 2-3 times per week and break roughly 30% of the time due to environment drift (different Node versions, missing env vars, OS package mismatches between laptops and the VM). The team has no automated tests running on deploy, no rollback mechanism, and onboarding a new developer takes 1-2 days of environment setup. Leadership has approved a 2-sprint initiative to containerize the app with Docker and introduce a CI/CD pipeline using GitHub Actions (the code already lives on GitHub). The target deployment environment is a single cloud VM that can run Docker; Kubernetes is explicitly out of scope for this phase. The app listens on port 3000, requires Node 20, uses environment variables for DATABASE_URL and STRIPE_KEY, and has a Jest test suite that runs in about 40 seconds. The team wants: (1) a Dockerfile that produces a small, reproducible image, (2) a GitHub Actions workflow that builds the image, runs tests, pushes to a registry, and triggers a deploy on merges to main, and (3) a README that lets any new developer run the app locally in under 10 minutes.

